Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the @paneer{250%g} into 2cm cubes.

Pour the cold @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tightly fitted #lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp}, cover with the lid and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to its lowest setting. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pan{} from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat the @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the paneer to the pan, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry until golden all over, ~{5-7%minutes}. Turn every 1-2 mins to ensure they don't burn. Once golden, transfer to a #plate{} lined with #kitchen paper{}.

Add the onion to the (now empty) pan. Reduce the heat to medium-high and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Then add the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g}(unusually tomato puree) and @north Indian style spice mix{1/2%tsp}. Fry until fragrant, stirring, ~{1%minute}. Add the @tomato passata{1} bowl, @water for the sauce{200%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Season with salt and pepper, stir to combine. Bring to the boil, lower the heat and simmer gently until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, add the paneer back into the pan along with the @peas{120%g} and the @mango chutney{40%g}. Cook until everything is piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and add more salt or pepper if needed.

When ready, divide the rice between your #bowls{} and spoon the Punjabi style matar paneer curry over the top. Add a dollop of @greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} to finish. Enjoy!

> This recipe serves 2 people.

> Nutrition per serving: 960 kcal, 45g fat, 28g saturated fat, 98g carbohydrates, 31g sugar, 41g protein, 2.4g sodium.